    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-06-29T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-06-29T11:00:00-05:00" n="1079"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1079">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.801/6–2949: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-06-29T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 29, 1949—5 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:24 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2518. Depintel June 27, 10 a. m.<note n="32" xml:id="d1079fn32">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Foreign Office states pressed by British shipping interests to clarify
                            Government position in Chinese Nationalist closure ports north of Min
                            River. Foreign Office informed Department that Foreign Office spokesman
                            would probably make statement Commons Wednesday or <pb facs="1125"
                                n="1115" xml:id="pg_1115"/> Thursday. As Coghill will not present
                            British reply to Canton Government until 30th, statement cannot be made
                            in Commons before Friday, if then.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Questioned re next step should Chinese Nationalist Government ignore
                            US–UK replies and bomb and shell US–UK ships and properties,
                                Scarlett<note n="33" xml:id="d1079fn33">Peter W. S. Y. Scarlett,
                                Head of the Far Eastern Department of the British Foreign
                                Office.</note> stated that would pose new problem for legal experts.
                            Would also bring forward clash between short term and long term policies
                            and objectives. Short term contemplates rehabilitation Shanghai and
                            revival British commercial and shipping interests by use British
                            influence and persuasion but thereby contributing to Chinese Communist
                            influence and power; long term contemplates prevention growth Communist
                            power and in pursuit thereof permitting Shanghai and other Chinese
                            cities to lapse into chaos and starvation. No decision yet.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
